### ─── Scenario 1: HTTP → webhook (direct) ───────────────────────────
### Binary content mode: Ce-Type matches HTTP-1 → result published to webhook.site
POST http://localhost:8880/command
Content-Type: application/json
Ce-Id: scenario1-bin-001
Ce-Specversion: 1.0
Ce-Type: com.example.http.command.webhook
Ce-Source: //test/http-client

{
  "name": "direct-to-webhook",
  "age": 28
}

### Structured content mode: same scenario, full CloudEvent as JSON body.
POST http://localhost:8880/command
Content-Type: application/cloudevents+json

{
  "specversion": "1.0",
  "id": "scenario1-struct-001",
  "type": "com.example.http.command.webhook",
  "source": "//test/http-client",
  "datacontenttype": "application/json",
  "data": {
    "name": "structured-to-webhook",
    "age": 30
  }
}

### ─── Scenario 2: HTTP → Pub/Sub → read from subscription → webhook ─
### Binary content mode: Ce-Type matches HTTP-2 → result published to Pub/Sub topic.
### PrincipalMux reads it as type "com.example.http.command.result" → PS-1 forwards to webhook.
POST http://localhost:8880/command
Content-Type: application/json
Ce-Id: scenario2-bin-001
Ce-Specversion: 1.0
Ce-Type: com.example.http.command
Ce-Source: //test/http-client

{
  "name": "via-pubsub-to-webhook",
  "age": 25
}

### Structured content mode: same two-leg flow via Pub/Sub.
POST http://localhost:8880/command
Content-Type: application/cloudevents+json

{
  "specversion": "1.0",
  "id": "scenario2-struct-001",
  "type": "com.example.http.command",
  "source": "//test/http-client",
  "datacontenttype": "application/json",
  "data": {
    "name": "structured-via-pubsub",
    "age": 22
  }
}

### ─── Fallback: Plain HTTP (no CE headers) ──────────────────────────
### No CloudEvents headers → subscriber builds CE with fallback type "com.example.http.command".
### Matches HTTP-3 by JMESPath → result published to Pub/Sub topic.
POST http://localhost:8880/command
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "name": "webhook",
  "age": 21
}
